<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="339" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,933]" box="[199,973,151,176]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,151,176]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Description.</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity box="[496,634,151,176]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="7.3" metricValueMin="6.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="339" unit="mm" value="7.0" valueMax="7.3" valueMin="6.7">6.7–7.3 mm</quantity>
; forebody length 
<quantity box="[830,968,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.55" metricValueMax="3.7" metricValueMin="3.4" pageId="6" pageNumber="339" unit="mm" value="3.55" valueMax="3.7" valueMin="3.4">3.4–3.7 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,933]" box="[199,902,188,213]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">
Body (
<figureCitation box="[275,341,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,2015,2038]" captionTargetBox="[159,1424,1311,1990]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[150,1437,1299,2005]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 9. Habitus of new species 6 – Nazeris huapingensis; 7 – N. alatus; 8 – N. exilis; 9 – N. chenyanae. Scale bars: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/852918/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) dark brown; antennae and legs yellowish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[273,354,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 24" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1680,1703]" captionTargetBox="[184,1404,405,1636]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,375,1659]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 24. Nazeris exilis 20 – forebody; 21 – male sternite VII; 22 – male sternite VIII; 23 – aedeagus, in ventral view; 24 – aedeagus, in lateral view. Scale bars: 20: 1 mm, 21 – 24: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/852924/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as wide; punctation very dense, moderately coarse, distinctly umbilicate, interstices without microsculpture; postocular portion approximately 1.6 times as long as eye length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[325,407,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 24" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1680,1703]" captionTargetBox="[184,1404,405,1636]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,375,1659]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 24. Nazeris exilis 20 – forebody; 21 – male sternite VII; 22 – male sternite VIII; 23 – aedeagus, in ventral view; 24 – aedeagus, in lateral view. Scale bars: 20: 1 mm, 21 – 24: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/852924/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
) 1.15–1.19 times as long as wide, 0.97–1.03 times as long and 0.85–0.88 times as broad as head; punctation non-umbilicate, moderately dense and as coarse as that of head; midline with narrow impunctate elevation in posteriorly half; interstices without microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[285,370,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 24" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1680,1703]" captionTargetBox="[184,1404,405,1636]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,375,1659]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 24. Nazeris exilis 20 – forebody; 21 – male sternite VII; 22 – male sternite VIII; 23 – aedeagus, in ventral view; 24 – aedeagus, in lateral view. Scale bars: 20: 1 mm, 21 – 24: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/852924/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
) 0.63–0.69 times as long as wide, 0.54–0.60 times as long and 0.95–1.00 times as broad as pronotum; punctation as dense as, and less coarse than that of pronotum; interstices without microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Abdomen with punctation dense and rather coarse on tergites III, dense and less coarse on tergite VI–V, moderately dense and fine on tergites VII–VIII; interstices lacking microsculpture.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">
<emphasis box="[199,257,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Male</emphasis>
. Sternite VII (
<figureCitation box="[426,509,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 24" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1680,1703]" captionTargetBox="[184,1404,405,1636]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,375,1659]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 24. Nazeris exilis 20 – forebody; 21 – male sternite VII; 22 – male sternite VIII; 23 – aedeagus, in ventral view; 24 – aedeagus, in lateral view. Scale bars: 20: 1 mm, 21 – 24: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/852924/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
) with posterior margin weakly prominent at middle. Sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[1284,1368,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 24" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1680,1703]" captionTargetBox="[184,1404,405,1636]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,375,1659]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 24. Nazeris exilis 20 – forebody; 21 – male sternite VII; 22 – male sternite VIII; 23 – aedeagus, in ventral view; 24 – aedeagus, in lateral view. Scale bars: 20: 1 mm, 21 – 24: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/852924/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
) with triangular posterior excision. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[613,744,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 24" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1680,1703]" captionTargetBox="[184,1404,405,1636]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,375,1659]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 24. Nazeris exilis 20 – forebody; 21 – male sternite VII; 22 – male sternite VIII; 23 – aedeagus, in ventral view; 24 – aedeagus, in lateral view. Scale bars: 20: 1 mm, 21 – 24: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/852924/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Figs 23, 24</figureCitation>
) weakly sclerotized; ventral process long, with pair of small laminae in basal third, apex divided into two straight branches in ventral view; dorso-lateral apophyses slender, slightly curved ventrally in lateral view, not reaching apex of ventral process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="339" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,558,692,717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Distribution and habitat data.</emphasis>
The species is known only from Huaping in northeast 
<collectingRegion box="[1176,1273,692,717]" country="China" name="Guangxi" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Guangxi</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[1288,1373,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[150,1437,900,1709]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[150,1437,900,1709]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 30. Map showing the distribution of Nazeris in Guangxi A – N. dayaoensis; B – N. luoi; C – N. tani; D – N. qini; E – N. megalobus; F – N. grandis; G – N. damingshanus; H – N. longilobus; I – N. bihamatus; J – N. latilobatus; K – N. obtortus; L – N. huapingensis; M – N. alatus; N – N. exilis; O – N. chenyanae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/852928/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). The specimens were collected by sifting leaf litter at altitudes of 
<quantity box="[826,984,728,752]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.26" metricValueMax="1.3199999999999998" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="339" unit="m" value="1260.0" valueMax="1320.0" valueMin="1200.0">1200–1320 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,434,764,789]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
This species is very similar in general appearance and aedeagal characters to 
<taxonomicName authority="Hu &amp; Li" authorityName="Hu &amp; Li" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Nazeris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="339" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="divisus">
<emphasis box="[1324,1436,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">N. divisus</emphasis>
Hu &amp; Li
</taxonomicName>
, but can be separated by larger body size and a narrower and longer ventral process of the aedeagus (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 24" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1680,1703]" captionTargetBox="[184,1404,405,1636]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1437,375,1659]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 24. Nazeris exilis 20 – forebody; 21 – male sternite VII; 22 – male sternite VIII; 23 – aedeagus, in ventral view; 24 – aedeagus, in lateral view. Scale bars: 20: 1 mm, 21 – 24: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/852924/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="339" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,871,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="339">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet (Latin, adjective: slender) alludes to the very slender dorso-lateral apophyses of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
